videoTitle: how weâ€™re *actually* getting jobs in 2025 #jobsearch
commentText: You may get bites from very small firms. For larger firms, this is worse than contacting recruiter directly. Interviewing screening and such are usually side things for hiring managers and are more focused on their primary senior job duties. They will more than likely get annoyed and ignore it completely. Especially these days where applicant to role ratios are wack. Chances are they already have dozens of folks contacting them directly.  Networking helps a lot: job fairs, friends, family, hobby groups. Have multiple people look over your resume. Practice interviewing. Other than that it's a number game.

commentText: Excellent advice.  We started out using a relocation service and were not satisfied.  We ended up doing it ourselves with the help of expats that were very helpful with advice and steps.  The biggest revelation for us was that we did not have to be skillful in French to get things done.  We found the apartment, set up the bank account and arranged phone and internet service ourselves with little problem.  In all cases we attempted to converse in French but they generally would converse in English.  The representative at Credit Agricole amazingly apologized for her poor English.  The biggest takeaway is that fear should not control the decision and there are many expats that can help without charging you. This is our experience in a larger city which could be different in smaller cities and villages.

commentText: Whether you need certain consulting services can depend on your individual circumstances. I moved to France earlier this month as a single retiree. I didn't need an immigration attorney to help me apply for my long-stay visa. That's a couple of thousand dollars or more saved. However, I did use a housing search consultant while still living in the US. That was money well spent because the renter/landlord relationship, required paperwork and requirement of a guarantor are processes so different from what we're used to. Plus I calculated I would save money by not paying for a long-term rental in France while apartment hunting. The leasing agent set up my electric utility and the search consultant helped me set up a bank account as part of their fee. I did the cell/Internet service myself.

commentText: I *think* you can inquire to the Chambre de Commerce of the region or department where you need the service. But they will not give any rating.  There are English realtors working in France. It can help to be able to contact a company where the owner speaks English. (There is one I know in the nearby village from you).  If you look on Internet, you will find mostly stories about things that went wrong. When someone has no problem, he will not document about it. When I was looking to make my visa, all I found was negative. And my processing had been seamless. I took the time to comment about it, but it is uncommon. So be careful about all the  negative experiences you can read about.  If you are about to relocate, it is because you have strong motivations, changing continent is not something you do on a whim. So it should beat the anguish about the paperwork.  The modern tools, Internet, automatic translation, make it really easy to work out the problems yourself. If not, maybe you are not made to live abroad.

Be careful: even if you're highly paid, you will usually need a guarantor unless you can present at least your last three payslips. And of course, you'll need proof that the guarantor is financially capable of covering the rent if you canâ€™t. Some landlords even ask to see your income tax documentsâ€”technically illegal, but itâ€™s often a case of â€œcomply or miss out.â€  When moving in, make sure the handover certificate (Ã©tat des lieux) is filled out completely and accurately. If you sign for 10 holes in the kitchen tiles instead of the actual 11, youâ€™ll likely be charged for repairs.  When moving out, donâ€™t accept any â€œNVâ€ (meaning â€œnot verifiedâ€) entries in the final handover certificate. This is often used as a loophole to claim damages later. At the very least, it can delay the return of your deposit (usually the equivalent of three months' rent). They may even deduct indemnities for imaginary damagesâ€”illegal, but who has the time and money to fight over 100 or 200 euros?

commentText: Renting is definitely the hardest part, even for French people. The rules vary greatly whether you're looking at an area with high renting pressure or not, like anywhere else I guess. landlords can have illegal requests and it is up to you and your will to get the house/flat to accept them. On the other side they can have very little requirements if they're desperately looking for a renter (landlords pay taxes - "taxe fonciÃ¨re" - even for an empty property). They can also increase the deposit (which cannot be more than 2 months worth of rental) and deposits are sometimes difficult to get back at the end.
